{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17624971","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17624971"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:20:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:20:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16958"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16958","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16958"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.93,0.02,0.02,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9648"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68060"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9648","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9648"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16958"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53517"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"8411"},{"type":"tags","id":"8421"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22762"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22766"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68060","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68060"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of gap junctions in cardiac muscle?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Control blood flow through coronary vessels","Allow direct electrical coupling between adjacent cells","Generate action potentials in pacemaker cells","Provide mechanical strength between muscle fibers","Regulate calcium release from internal stores"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGap junctions allow direct electrical coupling between adjacent cells\u003C/strong\u003E via connexon channels. Connexon channels are composed of six protein subunits called connexins, which arrange themselves in a hexagonal structure to form a pore. Each connexon from one cell aligns with a connexon from an adjacent cell to create a continuous aqueous channel that spans the gap between the two cells. These specialized protein channels enable ions to flow directly between neighboring cardiac muscle cells, facilitating the rapid propagation of electrical signals and ensuring synchronized contraction of the heart.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Ch3\u003EExplanation of Incorrect Options:\u003C/h3\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProviding mechanical strength\u003C/strong\u003E: This is the role of desmosomes and adherens junctions within intercalated discs, not gap junctions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGenerating action potentials in pacemaker cells\u003C/strong\u003E: This is achieved through specialized ion channels in the sinoatrial node, not gap junctions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERegulating calcium release from internal stores\u003C/strong\u003E: This function is performed by ryanodine receptors in the sarcoplasmic reticulum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EControlling blood flow through coronary vessels\u003C/strong\u003E: This is regulated by vascular smooth muscle and endothelial cells, not by gap junctions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGap junctions are essential for the heart\u0027s role as an electrical syncytium, allowing coordinated depolarization and contraction of cardiac muscle cells. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cardiac muscle cells are connected by intercalated discs containing gap junctions that allow rapid electrical signal propagation.","Gap junctions in cardiac muscle enable the heart to function as a syncytium, allowing coordinated contraction.","Connexons form channels between adjacent cardiac cells, permitting direct ion flow and electrical coupling."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53517"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16958"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53517","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53517"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-08T21:03:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-08T21:04:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9648"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68060"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving informat